00:10:52.390 --> 00:10:55.735
so they can explore Masal
city, I took them to Dubai,

00:10:55.735 --> 00:10:57.559
I brought them here.

00:10:57.559 --> 00:10:59.350
In the end, in that
one trip, I asked them,

00:10:59.350 --> 00:11:00.430
what was your best experience?

00:11:00.430 --> 00:11:01.513
And they said, Bhutan was.

00:11:01.513 --> 00:11:02.402
And I said why?

00:11:02.402 --> 00:11:04.610
You didn't want to go there,
and now, all of a sudden

00:11:04.610 --> 00:11:06.276
that's like one of
your favorite places.

00:11:06.276 --> 00:11:06.970
How come?

00:11:06.970 --> 00:11:08.386
They said, you
know, when we first

00:11:08.386 --> 00:11:10.540
arrived there, the one
thing that we explored

00:11:10.540 --> 00:11:13.840
was the fact that they had
such beautiful clean water.

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:16.780
Some of these students had never
seen such clean, natural water

00:11:16.780 --> 00:11:17.800
in rivers.

00:11:17.800 --> 00:11:20.170
Because a lot of
them are polluted.

00:11:20.170 --> 00:11:21.730
Many of them had
never seen a place

00:11:21.730 --> 00:11:23.914
that sequestered more
carbon than they made,

00:11:23.914 --> 00:11:25.330
because they live
next door to it.

00:11:25.330 --> 00:11:27.941
But it's just,
like, unbelievable.

00:11:27.941 --> 00:11:29.440
They run out-- as
soon as I arrived,

00:11:29.440 --> 00:11:31.300
we all arrived into Bhutan.

00:11:31.300 --> 00:11:32.620
We're at Paro airport.

00:11:32.620 --> 00:11:33.710
We're in a bus.

00:11:33.710 --> 00:11:35.560
We're going along
to, like, Thimphu.

00:11:35.560 --> 00:11:37.540
The bus stops for some reason.

00:11:37.540 --> 00:11:38.650
I'm, like, snoozing off.

00:11:38.650 --> 00:11:42.194
All the kids run off, and
I'm like, what's happened?

00:11:42.194 --> 00:11:44.110
And I come outside, and
they're taking selfies

00:11:44.110 --> 00:11:45.312
with the clear water.

00:11:45.312 --> 00:11:47.770
And I'm thinking, why are you
taking a selfie with a river?

00:11:47.770 --> 00:11:48.910
And that's the point.

00:11:48.910 --> 00:11:51.210
It was the fact that they
had lived such clean air,

00:11:51.210 --> 00:11:52.960
that when they go back
to Ahmedabad, which

00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:55.810
is one of the top two
polluted cities in India,

00:11:55.810 --> 00:11:59.030
they realize that other
things were possible, right?

00:11:59.030 --> 00:12:00.880
I took them equally to Japan.

00:12:00.880 --> 00:12:02.470
And in Japan, they
realize that what?

00:12:02.470 --> 00:12:05.110
32 different types of recycling?

00:12:05.110 --> 00:12:07.090
And you've got clear streets.

00:12:07.090 --> 00:12:08.330
I mean, who clears them up?

00:12:08.330 --> 00:12:10.042
Well, the community does.

00:12:10.042 --> 00:12:11.750
The community clears
up the streets, man?

00:12:11.750 --> 00:12:12.631
And I'm, like, yeah!

00:12:12.631 --> 00:12:13.630
It's called [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:13.630 --> 00:12:15.370
Every month everyone comes
out with a broomstick

00:12:15.370 --> 00:12:16.660
and they all clean it up.

00:12:16.660 --> 00:12:19.120
And you go to a Japanese
school, the kids come out once,

00:12:19.120 --> 00:12:21.389
half an hour, an
hour during the day.

00:12:21.389 --> 00:12:23.430
And they will come and
clean up the whole school.

00:12:23.430 --> 00:12:24.471
Are they paid to do that?

00:12:24.471 --> 00:12:25.820
I said no.

00:12:25.820 --> 00:12:28.970
You know, they don't have
maids and someone to clean up.

00:12:28.970 --> 00:12:30.270
I said no.

00:12:30.270 --> 00:12:31.533
That was a joke, [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:31.533 --> 00:12:36.985
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:36.985 --> 00:12:38.380
So then I really wanted--

00:12:38.380 --> 00:12:42.010
I sort of explored the
research angle of it.

00:12:42.010 --> 00:12:43.640
But another thing I
really wanted to do

00:12:43.640 --> 00:12:45.931
was to take some of these
students on a longer journey.

00:12:45.931 --> 00:12:48.970
So I took about six different
research projects, all related

00:12:48.970 --> 00:12:50.069
to recycling.

00:12:50.069 --> 00:12:52.610
Because I strongly sense that
our relationship, not just with

00:12:52.610 --> 00:12:55.750
the physical environment
affecting our brain

00:12:55.750 --> 00:12:58.840
and changing our
chemistry, but also--

00:12:58.840 --> 00:13:02.249
if we got them to
study the way that--

00:13:02.249 --> 00:13:03.790
I don't know if
you've been to India.

00:13:03.790 --> 00:13:06.739
If you have, you'll
understand and agree

00:13:06.739 --> 00:13:08.530
with me-- is that you
walk down the street,

00:13:08.530 --> 00:13:10.530
and you've just got piles
of rubbish everywhere.

00:13:10.530 --> 00:13:13.397
And they're informal, and
no one cleans them up.

00:13:13.397 --> 00:13:14.980
And if they do get
cleaned up, they're

00:13:14.980 --> 00:13:16.672
put in an informal
landfill site.

00:13:16.672 --> 00:13:18.130
And you look at
them and you think,

00:13:18.130 --> 00:13:22.400
well, you know, what
kind of normal is this?

00:13:22.400 --> 00:13:23.680
What kind of normal is this?

00:13:23.680 --> 00:13:24.850
This is the norm.

00:13:24.850 --> 00:13:27.269
Meaning, every time I walk
out, that's a blind spot.

00:13:27.269 --> 00:13:28.060
That doesn't exist.

00:13:28.060 --> 00:13:29.184
What are you talking about?

00:13:29.184 --> 00:13:31.667
I can't see it anymore, because
that's become my normal.

00:13:31.667 --> 00:13:34.000
And it's interesting, because
if you were to clean it up

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:35.800
for about 30 days,
let's say, you'd

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:37.520
make an imprint of a clean spot.

00:13:37.520 --> 00:13:38.470
And now, if there
was any rubbish,

00:13:38.470 --> 00:13:40.303
it's like, someone's
put some rubbish there.

00:13:40.303 --> 00:13:41.980
And it's really
interesting how habits

00:13:41.980 --> 00:13:45.160
are formed through the
visual relationship

00:13:45.160 --> 00:13:46.612
that we have with cities.

00:13:46.612 --> 00:13:48.820
So I wanted to explore that
with some of my students,

00:13:48.820 --> 00:13:50.110
and I did that.

00:13:50.110 --> 00:13:52.820
And the informal sector of
waste and how, where it goes.

00:13:52.820 --> 00:13:54.880
There was a whole black
market of waste, which

00:13:54.880 --> 00:13:56.940
we picked up on and documented.

00:13:56.940 --> 00:13:59.530
But then what I wanted to do
was give them an opportunity.

00:13:59.530 --> 00:14:02.030
And also a lot of the
people that lived in

00:14:02.030 --> 00:14:05.470
Ahmedabad an
opportunity to explore

00:14:05.470 --> 00:14:08.740
what it meant to be
inspired by a fellow Indian.

00:14:08.740 --> 00:14:09.790
No, not a foreigner.

00:14:09.790 --> 00:14:11.248
No, not someone
that you could say,

00:14:11.248 --> 00:14:13.360
well, they went to
Harvard University.

00:14:13.360 --> 00:14:15.730
But somebody that
could have been

00:14:15.730 --> 00:14:19.180
a neighbor down the street.

00:14:19.180 --> 00:14:21.910
And it was like, wow, how do I
find people that could inspire

00:14:21.910 --> 00:14:23.590
them and that they
could explore what

00:14:23.590 --> 00:14:27.239
it meant to be an Indian
living in today's India.

00:14:27.239 --> 00:14:29.530
But those who were actually
challenging the same things

00:14:29.530 --> 00:14:30.930
that they were living
through, but ignoring,

00:14:30.930 --> 00:14:32.410
and that was a blind spot.

00:14:32.410 --> 00:14:33.990
So I picked some
incredible people.

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:35.460
I don't know if
you remember, there

00:14:35.460 --> 00:14:38.974
was a documentary recently
where the edible spoons.

00:14:38.974 --> 00:14:40.390
You know, like
National Geographic

00:14:40.390 --> 00:14:41.600
did like the edible spoons.

00:14:41.600 --> 00:14:44.590
And you know, how many single
use plastics do we use?

00:14:44.590 --> 00:14:46.360
But this guy came
along and said,

00:14:46.360 --> 00:14:47.890
forget throwing them away.

00:14:47.890 --> 00:14:49.750
Let's make them edible.

00:14:49.750 --> 00:14:53.380
And so he created these
lentil-based spoons and things

00:14:53.380 --> 00:14:54.920
that people could
actually eat with.

00:14:54.920 --> 00:14:57.430
And so we invited him over
to be one of the speakers.

00:14:57.430 --> 00:14:59.710
And I kind of wanted
a Ted style, you know,

00:14:59.710 --> 00:15:01.872
inspirational 20 minutes
that you can explore.

00:15:01.872 --> 00:15:03.580
What have I done with
some of the biggest

00:15:03.580 --> 00:15:04.820
challenges of India?

00:15:04.820 --> 00:15:07.360
And that was the
first talk series

00:15:07.360 --> 00:15:11.720
that we created in January,
followed by Maker Fest.

00:15:11.720 --> 00:15:14.570
So you know, we really want
to go into the grassroots

00:15:14.570 --> 00:15:16.730
innovation and bring that out.

00:15:16.730 --> 00:15:21.380
So really, one of my
inspirations from childhood

00:15:21.380 --> 00:15:22.954
has been Sir David Attenborough.

00:15:22.954 --> 00:15:24.870
I don't know if you
remember him from England.

00:15:24.870 --> 00:15:26.510
You might remember his voice.

00:15:26.510 --> 00:15:29.270
And it was the-- he's
documenting the way that people

00:15:29.270 --> 00:15:31.520
live, Planet Earth, you know.

00:15:31.520 --> 00:15:34.970
He'll talk about the story and
the narrative behind the way

00:15:34.970 --> 00:15:36.319
that this animal is doing this.

00:15:36.319 --> 00:15:37.610
And look at the way that he is.

00:15:37.610 --> 00:15:38.990
And the reason
why he's doing it.

00:15:38.990 --> 00:15:43.030
And it was this beautiful
narrative, Planet Earth.

00:15:43.030 --> 00:15:45.770
But I completely get
what he's saying here.

00:15:45.770 --> 00:15:47.870
And that is that
no one will protect

00:15:47.870 --> 00:15:50.240
what they don't care
about, and no one

00:15:50.240 --> 00:15:53.310
will care about what they
have never experienced.

00:15:53.310 --> 00:15:55.700
So how do we create these
physical experiences?

00:15:55.700 --> 00:15:58.190
Because I think an education
and experience is not just

00:15:58.190 --> 00:16:00.780
in the head, right?

00:16:00.780 --> 00:16:02.300
If it was, then
I'd just give you

00:16:02.300 --> 00:16:05.200
some kind of augmented
reality or virtual reality.

00:16:05.200 --> 00:16:06.090
And you live there.

00:16:06.090 --> 00:16:09.180
And I'm sure you'll get
some physical repercussions

00:16:09.180 --> 00:16:10.740
of that relationship, too.

00:16:10.740 --> 00:16:14.250
So one of the things that we
ended up doing in Goa this year

00:16:14.250 --> 00:16:18.300
was to question-- where
can you hide waste?

00:16:18.300 --> 00:16:20.520
Where is it on Earth
you can put it?

00:16:20.520 --> 00:16:22.050
Can I put it under your desk?

00:16:22.050 --> 00:16:24.027
And the lady says no.

00:16:24.027 --> 00:16:25.110
Can I put it in your room?

00:16:25.110 --> 00:16:26.110
I mean, you're the
one who bought it.

00:16:26.110 --> 00:16:26.950
You keep it.

00:16:26.950 --> 00:16:29.399
Not my responsibility, why
are you giving it to me?

00:16:29.399 --> 00:16:30.940
No, I'm not going
to keep it my room.

00:16:30.940 --> 00:16:31.440
Why not?

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:32.620
It's yours!

00:16:32.620 --> 00:16:35.280
See if you were to live with
your waste for one week,

00:16:35.280 --> 00:16:37.280
in your room, in your
bedroom, like turn around,

00:16:37.280 --> 00:16:39.375
[SPITTING NOISE],,
where would you go?

00:16:39.375 --> 00:16:42.867
For how long could you live
with your own waste, right?

00:16:42.867 --> 00:16:45.450
And it's interesting, because
if I were to put all of my waste

00:16:45.450 --> 00:16:46.920
on a mountain,
right, I don't know

00:16:46.920 --> 00:16:48.211
how big that mountain would be.

00:16:48.211 --> 00:16:50.500
And I've started to
realize, oh, my god.

00:16:50.500 --> 00:16:51.600
Where is that going?

00:16:51.600 --> 00:16:53.520
So where are we
hiding our waste?

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:55.290
And so that is a question.

00:16:55.290 --> 00:16:57.199
We then put a whole
installation together.

00:16:57.199 --> 00:16:59.490
And the Indian government
was really impressed with it.

00:16:59.490 --> 00:17:01.698
They asked us, can we make
it permanent installation?

00:17:01.698 --> 00:17:04.770
So they gave us a
shipping container,

00:17:04.770 --> 00:17:07.109
and then we painted
it all black.

00:17:07.109 --> 00:17:10.500
We put these
incredible UV sort of--

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:12.540
using blacklight sort
of paints in there,

00:17:12.540 --> 00:17:14.339
and then we took
them on a minijourney

00:17:14.339 --> 00:17:16.170
around this installation.

00:17:16.170 --> 00:17:20.040
And the point of it was
what is a seahorse doing

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:21.510
holding a straw?

00:17:21.510 --> 00:17:24.569
It's, like, why are there
plastics in the ocean?

00:17:24.569 --> 00:17:25.932
Who does the sea belong to?

00:17:25.932 --> 00:17:27.390
And then as you go
through, there's

00:17:27.390 --> 00:17:31.969
like a very kiddie friendly and
adult friendly sort of dialogue

00:17:31.969 --> 00:17:33.510
that we create with
people as they're

00:17:33.510 --> 00:17:35.100
going through the installation.

00:17:35.100 --> 00:17:36.641
Got to a point at
the back where they

00:17:36.641 --> 00:17:40.490
had all these
beautiful jellyfish,

00:17:40.490 --> 00:17:42.030
and they're just
jellyfish, right?

00:17:42.030 --> 00:17:43.380
And you're looking at the
back, and you're, like, wow,

00:17:43.380 --> 00:17:45.119
the kids are like
they're jellyfish!

00:17:45.119 --> 00:17:46.410
Are you sure they're jellyfish?

00:17:46.410 --> 00:17:46.909
Yes!

00:17:46.909 --> 00:17:48.210
They're jellyfish.

00:17:48.210 --> 00:17:50.070
And then I'm, like, wrong.

00:17:50.070 --> 00:17:52.372
And like you, this
turtle has no idea

00:17:52.372 --> 00:17:53.580
that that is not a jellyfish.

00:17:53.580 --> 00:17:55.111
It's a plastic bag.

00:17:55.111 --> 00:17:56.610
And so it is really
this opportunity

00:17:56.610 --> 00:17:58.656
that I had to
question the plastics,

00:17:58.656 --> 00:18:00.530
but through the lifestyles
that we're living.

00:18:00.530 --> 00:18:03.060
And I think just on
the right-hand side

00:18:03.060 --> 00:18:05.970
of this picture, you'll
get to see the shrine

00:18:05.970 --> 00:18:08.680
that I put together for all of
the different kinds of plastics

00:18:08.680 --> 00:18:09.960
that anyone could have had.

00:18:09.960 --> 00:18:13.020
So then turned to them and said,
oh, is this your plastic bag?

00:18:13.020 --> 00:18:13.710
I don't know!

00:18:13.710 --> 00:18:14.880
Could it be?

00:18:14.880 --> 00:18:16.180
Could it be mine?

00:18:16.180 --> 00:18:17.802
You know, is that your straw?

00:18:17.802 --> 00:18:20.010
And then to sort of explore
this dialogue of plastics

00:18:20.010 --> 00:18:22.867
and plastic diet, it's
like a plastic footprint.

00:18:22.867 --> 00:18:24.450
And then the other
thing that I really

00:18:24.450 --> 00:18:27.420
want to explore through this
installation was microplastics.

00:18:27.420 --> 00:18:30.580
We talk about plastics
being in the ecosystem.

00:18:30.580 --> 00:18:32.710
But are we consuming
that plastic, too?

00:18:32.710 --> 00:18:35.190
And there is research in
so many different countries

00:18:35.190 --> 00:18:36.024
now, India as well--

00:18:36.024 --> 00:18:37.523
AUDIENCE: There's
a documentary that

00:18:37.523 --> 00:18:39.665
says that scientists
couldn't find a single water

00:18:39.665 --> 00:18:42.165
sample from the entire world
that doesn't have microplastics

00:18:42.165 --> 00:18:43.500
in it.

00:18:43.500 --> 00:18:45.930
TIA KANSARA HON FRIBA: That's
shocking and scares me.

00:18:45.930 --> 00:18:48.750
So what he said was that
scientists cannot find a single

00:18:48.750 --> 00:18:51.540
sample of water around the
world that doesn't have plastic

00:18:51.540 --> 00:18:52.620
inside it.

00:18:52.620 --> 00:18:55.260
Now what's really interesting,
and most of our water bodies

00:18:55.260 --> 00:18:58.380
are completely connected,
in most of our water bodies,

00:18:58.380 --> 00:19:00.470
a lot of that plastic
comes together.

00:19:00.470 --> 00:19:02.370
And that's why we
got these big, like,

00:19:02.370 --> 00:19:04.740
Ellen MacArthur has
traveled around the world

00:19:04.740 --> 00:19:07.050
and found out that there's
huge garbage patches which

00:19:07.050 --> 00:19:09.000
are the size of countries.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.490
Like, there's one the size
of France floating about.

00:19:11.490 --> 00:19:12.990
And there's no sun
that goes through

00:19:12.990 --> 00:19:16.140
to photosynthesize the algae.

00:19:16.140 --> 00:19:17.640
But what's really
fascinating for me

00:19:17.640 --> 00:19:20.520
is that microplastics
that break down are

00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:22.380
found in the underwater.

00:19:22.380 --> 00:19:24.615
But they're also
found in the animals.

00:19:24.615 --> 00:19:26.580
And they're also found in us.

00:19:26.580 --> 00:19:29.790
And what's that stage where the
plastic that we're putting out

00:19:29.790 --> 00:19:33.097
in the world comes back and
hits us into our stomachs?

00:19:33.097 --> 00:19:34.680
I wonder if there
is a way that now we

00:19:34.680 --> 00:19:37.172
can actually start analyzing
how many plastics exist in us.

00:19:37.172 --> 00:19:38.880
There's a bit of a
grim story, I suppose,

00:19:38.880 --> 00:19:40.080
and "The Times of
India" picked up on it

00:19:40.080 --> 00:19:41.820
and said that there
are some things

00:19:41.820 --> 00:19:44.040
that we should be
able to communicate

00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:45.410
through an installation.

00:19:45.410 --> 00:19:48.450
The Hindostan waste plant
has put that installation

00:19:48.450 --> 00:19:49.170
on their ground.

00:19:49.170 --> 00:19:51.480
So if any of you are
ever going to Goa,

00:19:51.480 --> 00:19:53.310
you are welcome to
go and visit it.

00:19:53.310 --> 00:19:55.500
But the point of the
insulation wasn't-- oh, my god,

00:19:55.500 --> 00:19:57.570
plastics are taking
over the world.

00:19:57.570 --> 00:19:59.850
It was what are the three
things that you can do, now

00:19:59.850 --> 00:20:01.620
that you walk out of
here, that can have

00:20:01.620 --> 00:20:03.510
a huge impact on Planet Earth?

00:20:03.510 --> 00:20:05.640
One of them, say
no to plastic bags,

00:20:05.640 --> 00:20:08.550
like single use plastic
bags or straws, right?

00:20:08.550 --> 00:20:09.460
Get your own straw.

00:20:09.460 --> 00:20:11.040
And just like when you're
about to order your food--

00:20:11.040 --> 00:20:13.456
and I've got preferences, I
don't like onions, let's say--

00:20:13.456 --> 00:20:14.950
then you tell people, don't you?

00:20:14.950 --> 00:20:17.620
You say, order that pizza
without onions, please.

00:20:17.620 --> 00:20:19.999
In the same way, order my
drink without a plastic straw.

00:20:19.999 --> 00:20:21.540
And now that I've
started doing that,

00:20:21.540 --> 00:20:23.331
I remember there was
a cafe down the street

00:20:23.331 --> 00:20:24.480
from the installation.

00:20:24.480 --> 00:20:26.210
People will at me and say,
you don't want a straw?

00:20:26.210 --> 00:20:27.126
I said, you know what?

00:20:27.126 --> 00:20:28.020
Do me a favor.

00:20:28.020 --> 00:20:30.240
Don't give anyone
this week a straw.

00:20:30.240 --> 00:20:31.960
But keep them there.

00:20:31.960 --> 00:20:34.930
Keep the straws there,
but don't give it to them.

00:20:34.930 --> 00:20:36.916
If they ask for it, they
know where to find it.

00:20:36.916 --> 00:20:39.040
So that's one step that
you could take that reduces

00:20:39.040 --> 00:20:40.240
the amount of plastic.

00:20:40.240 --> 00:20:43.060
But also, instead of having
multiple plastic bottles

00:20:43.060 --> 00:20:47.920
for water, how about if you had
one refillable water bottle,

00:20:47.920 --> 00:20:49.570
right, and one of
those big containers

00:20:49.570 --> 00:20:50.830
that you can actually
just refill instead

00:20:50.830 --> 00:20:52.030
of having plastic bottles.

00:20:52.030 --> 00:20:54.777
And every single day, I don't
know how many of these plastic

00:20:54.777 --> 00:20:56.110
bottles we seem to be consuming.

00:20:56.110 --> 00:20:58.450
So the point of it
wasn't how awful

00:20:58.450 --> 00:20:59.770
are we-- guilt tripping them.

00:20:59.770 --> 00:21:01.978
But actually getting them
to a point of saying, well,

00:21:01.978 --> 00:21:07.130
what can I do, now that I
can tangibly take that away.

00:21:07.130 --> 00:21:11.080
So now I'm moving into this
whole idea of dialogue.

00:21:11.080 --> 00:21:14.210
A lot of the communication
that we've been given

00:21:14.210 --> 00:21:17.100
is, I find, traumatizing.

00:21:17.100 --> 00:21:18.510
Makes me feel awful.

00:21:18.510 --> 00:21:22.370
I just want to like climb
underneath a blanket and cry.

00:21:22.370 --> 00:21:25.550
But what to do to have
this conversation?

00:21:25.550 --> 00:21:27.210
How did we get there?

00:21:27.210 --> 00:21:31.430
This is, like, imagine if every
single person on Planet Earth

00:21:31.430 --> 00:21:33.740
could have a
replenish lifestyle,

00:21:33.740 --> 00:21:37.560
could actually benefit
Planet Earth in some way.

00:21:37.560 --> 00:21:39.080
It's a dual thing.

00:21:39.080 --> 00:21:43.190
Number one is how do
we have that dialogue.

00:21:43.190 --> 00:21:45.440
I don't know if any of
you have been recipients

00:21:45.440 --> 00:21:46.370
of trolling on online.

00:21:46.370 --> 00:21:47.450
But I have.

00:21:47.450 --> 00:21:49.052
And it feels horrible, you know?

00:21:49.052 --> 00:21:50.510
It's, like, why
are you doing this?

00:21:50.510 --> 00:21:52.490
And you've never met me.

00:21:52.490 --> 00:21:55.490
And you've got an opinion
on who I am as a person.

00:21:55.490 --> 00:21:58.340
But that kind of dialogue
and the relationship

00:21:58.340 --> 00:22:01.100
that we have with one another,
I think, is really important.

00:22:01.100 --> 00:22:03.183
Because imagine if, like,
we're sitting at dinner,

00:22:03.183 --> 00:22:05.150
and three of you have
got your phones out.

00:22:05.150 --> 00:22:07.108
And your mom's sitting
there, and saying, well,

00:22:07.108 --> 00:22:08.024
put your phones away.

00:22:08.024 --> 00:22:09.440
Was there a
conversation we should

00:22:09.440 --> 00:22:12.260
have had at the beginning
to then get to a point

00:22:12.260 --> 00:22:14.930
where, at dinner, agreed--

00:22:14.930 --> 00:22:16.010
negotiations over here.

00:22:16.010 --> 00:22:17.640
We're compromising
on this table.

00:22:17.640 --> 00:22:19.850
We're not going to
have phones, fine.

00:22:19.850 --> 00:22:20.912
Cool.

00:22:20.912 --> 00:22:24.350
Do it before, do it after,
but not at the dinner table.

00:22:24.350 --> 00:22:26.300
Now that you've had
this conversation, that

00:22:26.300 --> 00:22:28.050
is the foundation, the
process that you're

00:22:28.050 --> 00:22:30.230
going to use for
that dialogue that

00:22:30.230 --> 00:22:32.690
is important for a lot
of the technology that

00:22:32.690 --> 00:22:34.270
is coming into our lives.

00:22:34.270 --> 00:22:37.726
So in the same
way, a lot of 4.0,

00:22:37.726 --> 00:22:39.350
so many different
kinds of technologies

00:22:39.350 --> 00:22:41.250
are actually on market.

00:22:41.250 --> 00:22:43.130
But is there a
point where we need

00:22:43.130 --> 00:22:46.880
to learn how to best
dialogue with each other

00:22:46.880 --> 00:22:52.700
to form some social parameters,
some kind of conversations,

00:22:52.700 --> 00:22:55.160
nonviolent communication,
that can actually

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:57.920
get us on par with where
we need to go next?

00:22:57.920 --> 00:23:00.380
And how do we have
that conversation?

00:23:00.380 --> 00:23:03.630
So I'd like to say, at the
beginning of this year,

00:23:03.630 --> 00:23:06.380
I came together with DX
Labs, based in San Francisco.

00:23:06.380 --> 00:23:08.430
They work with
Singularity as well.

00:23:08.430 --> 00:23:10.520
And one of the things
that I really wanted to do

00:23:10.520 --> 00:23:13.250
was write an article, a
story, about what would happen

00:23:13.250 --> 00:23:15.770
if you lived with a neuro link.

00:23:15.770 --> 00:23:21.900
If you, let's say, were
completely online with a brain.

00:23:21.900 --> 00:23:23.690
I mean a lot of
that technology has

00:23:23.690 --> 00:23:25.870
come into some sort of
research laboratories.

00:23:25.870 --> 00:23:27.920
And I kind of
imagine what it would

00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:31.162
feel like to have a
brain machine interface.

00:23:31.162 --> 00:23:33.620
But instead of getting to the
point where having opinions--

00:23:33.620 --> 00:23:37.430
for some reason, stories,
like, really cool stories,

00:23:37.430 --> 00:23:40.430
like, sci-fi stories
and videos and movies,

00:23:40.430 --> 00:23:44.160
can allow us to ask those
questions in a safe space.

00:23:44.160 --> 00:23:46.310
So I started to write.

00:23:46.310 --> 00:23:48.770
And on Medium, I
wrote this post,

00:23:48.770 --> 00:23:51.250
"Replenish, the Convergence
of AI and Ecology."

00:23:51.250 --> 00:23:52.640
And there's two parts.

00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:54.598
And I'd love to know what
you thought about it.

00:23:54.598 --> 00:23:56.720
But what was, for
me, really intriguing

00:23:56.720 --> 00:23:59.240
is that there
comes a point where

00:23:59.240 --> 00:24:01.190
technology and nature merge.

00:24:01.190 --> 00:24:02.750
Imagine-- you know,
you might know

00:24:02.750 --> 00:24:05.900
Meow-Meow, who's got a
biometric scanner in his arm.

00:24:05.900 --> 00:24:07.840
And then he sort of
uploads the data.

00:24:07.840 --> 00:24:10.610
So we're coming to that
point of quantified self.

00:24:10.610 --> 00:24:12.740
I've got a Fitbit on me.

00:24:12.740 --> 00:24:16.100
We're getting to that point
where we're merging with tech.

00:24:16.100 --> 00:24:20.240
And at that point,
at what point, yeah--

00:24:20.240 --> 00:24:22.250
where do we become
the technology

00:24:22.250 --> 00:24:24.774
that we're also
introducing into our lives?

00:24:24.774 --> 00:24:26.690
And it's a really
interesting question for me.

00:24:26.690 --> 00:24:28.940
Because imagine if
the whole of our brain

00:24:28.940 --> 00:24:31.940
was uploaded onto the internet,
and that brain could then

00:24:31.940 --> 00:24:34.550
be analyzed and your
thoughts analyzed

00:24:34.550 --> 00:24:37.700
and whatever kind of
interesting behaviors we had

00:24:37.700 --> 00:24:40.580
could, in some way, even be
controlled or manipulated?

00:24:40.580 --> 00:24:43.154
But if we had an opportunity to
actually enhance that and put

00:24:43.154 --> 00:24:45.320
that forward, and we could
have a dialogue about it,

00:24:45.320 --> 00:24:48.170
where would that dialogue go?

00:24:48.170 --> 00:24:50.780
But also about this sort
of-- the automation,

00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:54.050
I think, of life, the automation
of a lot of the challenges

00:24:54.050 --> 00:24:55.250
that we've got.

00:24:55.250 --> 00:24:58.940
Where do we get to a point
where that automation becomes

00:24:58.940 --> 00:25:03.170
with or without the direction
that we're giving it?

00:25:03.170 --> 00:25:06.230
Here's some of the research
that we did on the whole brain.

00:25:06.230 --> 00:25:08.180
But also, where would
we put that technology,

00:25:08.180 --> 00:25:09.800
and having
conversations about it.

00:25:09.800 --> 00:25:13.010
And it's been really interesting
to explore this technology

00:25:13.010 --> 00:25:15.350
through the lens of an
individual who would say,

00:25:15.350 --> 00:25:17.270
I would never have
something like that done.

00:25:17.270 --> 00:25:19.777
But to explore it through
a story is much easier.

00:25:19.777 --> 00:25:21.860
And so to have that
conversation, even though it's

00:25:21.860 --> 00:25:24.080
not real, is almost
easier for people

00:25:24.080 --> 00:25:25.910
to sort of interact with.

00:25:25.910 --> 00:25:30.030
So we talked about Industry
4.0 entering the market.

00:25:30.030 --> 00:25:33.170
But also, when it comes to the
sustainable development goals

00:25:33.170 --> 00:25:35.150
that the United
Nations have launched,

00:25:35.150 --> 00:25:38.980
was how much is
this industry worth?

00:25:38.980 --> 00:25:41.120
Should we really
bother about it?

00:25:41.120 --> 00:25:45.330
And the WEF has actually put
a sum, $2.5 trillion on it.

00:25:45.330 --> 00:25:48.770
I think the next step
is really to understand

00:25:48.770 --> 00:25:51.110
where we can go with that.

00:25:51.110 --> 00:25:55.490
If you had $2.5 trillion
of a budget towards this,

00:25:55.490 --> 00:25:57.344
where would we
direct our research?

00:25:57.344 --> 00:25:59.010
What kind of businesses
would we create?

00:25:59.010 --> 00:26:01.040
What kind of cities
would we design?

00:26:01.040 --> 00:26:06.350
So some of the work that I've
been doing here has been in--

00:26:06.350 --> 00:26:09.620
I mentioned the Gulf
benchmark on energy.

00:26:09.620 --> 00:26:12.666
What that then led
to was an article,

00:26:12.666 --> 00:26:14.290
I think in "The Gulf"
or "The National"

00:26:14.290 --> 00:26:16.150
that was too cold for comfort.

00:26:16.150 --> 00:26:18.089
I feel physical buildings
being way too cold,

00:26:18.089 --> 00:26:19.630
and people are
getting ill from them.

00:26:19.630 --> 00:26:21.160
And that was with the
National Bank of Abu Dhabi.

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:23.050
Some of the work that
I've done, and trying

00:26:23.050 --> 00:26:25.810
to explore whether it should
be a top down or a bottom up

00:26:25.810 --> 00:26:27.010
approach.

00:26:27.010 --> 00:26:29.370
Where are these smart
cities taking us?

00:26:29.370 --> 00:26:31.800
And where do we have an
opportunity to be part of that?

00:26:31.800 --> 00:26:34.780
There was a project that I
did with the Premier of South

00:26:34.780 --> 00:26:37.450
Australia, Jay
Weatherill, and it

00:26:37.450 --> 00:26:41.020
was really about understanding
what does carbon negative mean,

00:26:41.020 --> 00:26:42.760
or carbon neutral
mean, and where can we

00:26:42.760 --> 00:26:44.420
push the boundaries of that?

00:26:44.420 --> 00:26:49.030
So it's interesting,
because whoever we are,

00:26:49.030 --> 00:26:51.700
are based on the
experiences that we've had.

00:26:51.700 --> 00:26:55.000
But when we start to combine
our knowledge and experiences,

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:58.480
we almost actualize a
community of knowledge,

00:26:58.480 --> 00:26:59.950
like a collaboration.

00:26:59.950 --> 00:27:03.130
But it's going beyond that
that's really interesting

00:27:03.130 --> 00:27:03.970
to understand.

00:27:03.970 --> 00:27:06.190
How do we get to a point
where we can really

00:27:06.190 --> 00:27:09.070
explore all of our learnings
together through this,

00:27:09.070 --> 00:27:11.890
and with that, our fears?

00:27:11.890 --> 00:27:14.530
And this really goes back to
a very interesting project

00:27:14.530 --> 00:27:16.450
in the UK, which a
friend of mine has got.

00:27:16.450 --> 00:27:18.820
His name is Simon Gosling.

00:27:18.820 --> 00:27:20.930
And he's exploring
what smart means.

00:27:20.930 --> 00:27:23.410
So he brings people
into this future home

00:27:23.410 --> 00:27:25.830
and explores the dialogues
that he's having with them.

00:27:25.830 --> 00:27:29.140
So if you're ever in London, I'd
love to introduce you to him.

00:27:29.140 --> 00:27:31.540
And this is a very
small project that I've

00:27:31.540 --> 00:27:34.780
got with about 300
villages surrounding

00:27:34.780 --> 00:27:37.570
Surat which is one of
the fastest growing

00:27:37.570 --> 00:27:39.040
cities in India.

00:27:39.040 --> 00:27:41.230
But as you can see, one of
the big projects of India

00:27:41.230 --> 00:27:45.220
is [INAUDIBLE],, which is about
that kind of ideal village,

00:27:45.220 --> 00:27:47.554
and exploring what that means,
even though you walk down

00:27:47.554 --> 00:27:50.053
the street, and you've got these
piles and piles of rubbish.

00:27:50.053 --> 00:27:52.460
So how do we take this
whole replenish philosophy

00:27:52.460 --> 00:27:55.060
and plug it into
the rural sector

00:27:55.060 --> 00:27:57.700
and actually help
people to transition

00:27:57.700 --> 00:27:59.626
to that kind of a lifestyle?

00:27:59.626 --> 00:28:01.000
Another thing that
I did recently

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:02.980
was in Brazil,
where we celebrated

00:28:02.980 --> 00:28:05.140
a whole week of zero waste.

00:28:05.140 --> 00:28:07.180
And one of the most
exciting things that I saw

00:28:07.180 --> 00:28:12.100
was an actual
supermarket that is 96%--

00:28:12.100 --> 00:28:14.050
and it's a massive supermarket--

00:28:14.050 --> 00:28:17.590
[INAUDIBLE] market
that is 96% zero waste.

00:28:17.590 --> 00:28:21.970
And you know, we developed and
designed some ideas for Lisbon

00:28:21.970 --> 00:28:23.970
being a zero waste city.

00:28:23.970 --> 00:28:25.870
But I think we're
almost at that point

00:28:25.870 --> 00:28:28.210
where a lot of cities
and a lot of companies

00:28:28.210 --> 00:28:31.810
are actually taking on
much more practical levels

00:28:31.810 --> 00:28:35.920
of appreciating and translating
this kind of philosophy.

00:28:35.920 --> 00:28:38.500
So you can find out more
about me on our newsletter.

00:28:38.500 --> 00:28:41.380
I normally kind of post
any new bits or new pieces

00:28:41.380 --> 00:28:44.380
of information that I collect.

00:28:44.380 --> 00:28:48.550
The next steps for me really
are consolidating about 10

00:28:48.550 --> 00:28:53.770
years' worth of travel and
understanding what is next.

00:28:53.770 --> 00:28:56.366
Like, if we were to introduce
this whole economic paradigm,

00:28:56.366 --> 00:28:58.240
like, the World Replenish
Index, and you had,

00:28:58.240 --> 00:29:00.823
at the back of your bottles, and
everything that you consumed,

00:29:00.823 --> 00:29:05.630
a Replenish indicator, would
you live a replenish diet?

00:29:05.630 --> 00:29:07.930
And how much of that
would be your lifestyle?

00:29:07.930 --> 00:29:11.110
You know how-- let's
say I'm vegan, right?

00:29:11.110 --> 00:29:14.050
But I'm vegan in my
diet, not my lifestyle.

00:29:14.050 --> 00:29:17.860
How would I translate the
vegan to the lifestyle as well?

00:29:17.860 --> 00:29:20.500
How do I translate
this lifestyle

00:29:20.500 --> 00:29:22.930
into something that is
appropriate for Planet Earth?

00:29:22.930 --> 00:29:24.250
So I'm exploring these things.

00:29:24.250 --> 00:29:25.810
I was really grateful
to have shared

00:29:25.810 --> 00:29:29.069
some of my work with
you, but also some

00:29:29.069 --> 00:29:31.360
of the challenges and the
questions that are leading me

00:29:31.360 --> 00:29:33.040
and the vision that
I've got for it.

00:29:33.040 --> 00:29:37.180
I really hope that in
maybe 10 to 20 years' time,

00:29:37.180 --> 00:29:41.110
we can look back and say that
the planet that we live on

00:29:41.110 --> 00:29:43.782
is an ecosystem
that we're part of.

00:29:43.782 --> 00:29:45.490
But it's an ecosystem
that we're together

00:29:45.490 --> 00:29:51.160
with, that we can work together
on creating a replenish earth,

00:29:51.160 --> 00:29:53.005
replenishing lifestyle from.

00:29:53.005 --> 00:29:56.680
And I think there's these
ideas almost of, like,

00:29:56.680 --> 00:29:59.170
moving away from the
challenges of living

00:29:59.170 --> 00:30:01.140
in a lifestyle like this.

00:30:01.140 --> 00:30:02.650
And maybe it's going backwards.

00:30:02.650 --> 00:30:04.600
You know, going to live
in a village in India

00:30:04.600 --> 00:30:06.234
is not necessarily
the challenge.

00:30:06.234 --> 00:30:07.900
But exploring those
things in the cities

00:30:07.900 --> 00:30:10.540
and the buildings and the
companies that we live

00:30:10.540 --> 00:30:11.819
and work in.

00:30:11.819 --> 00:30:13.360
So thank you very
much for your time.

