me included, to believe
something that is the case.

00:42:35.950 --> 00:42:37.650
There is no status quo.

00:42:37.650 --> 00:42:41.010
Therefore, everything
can be questioned.

00:42:41.010 --> 00:42:42.090
The way that we live--

00:42:42.090 --> 00:42:43.710
I learned this when
I was in Japan.

00:42:43.710 --> 00:42:46.212
I remember coming from
England, 22 years old,

00:42:46.212 --> 00:42:47.670
just finished my
university degree.

00:42:47.670 --> 00:42:50.250
Arrived in Japan, and
they say, this is wrong.

00:42:50.250 --> 00:42:52.420
In England, OK, I'm
taking one example.

00:42:52.420 --> 00:42:54.420
In England, when you're
sitting next to somebody

00:42:54.420 --> 00:42:55.590
that you don't know
at the bus stop,

00:42:55.590 --> 00:42:57.089
you start talking
about the weather.

00:42:57.089 --> 00:42:59.355
But you'd normally
talk about how shit is.

00:42:59.355 --> 00:43:01.810
You're like, oh, the weather
is really bad, isn't it?

00:43:01.810 --> 00:43:03.400
And somebody turns around
and is, like, yeah, god,

00:43:03.400 --> 00:43:04.300
it's been raining all day.

00:43:04.300 --> 00:43:05.426
That could be good as well.

00:43:05.426 --> 00:43:06.758
The weather's really good today.

00:43:06.758 --> 00:43:07.610
Oh, oh, it's lovely.

00:43:07.610 --> 00:43:10.890
But it's an excuse to
have a chat with somebody.

00:43:10.890 --> 00:43:12.870
Well, I went to
Japan, and I started

00:43:12.870 --> 00:43:18.422
to use the negative to open up
dialogue, and it didn't work.

00:43:18.422 --> 00:43:19.380
I'm not being negative.

00:43:19.380 --> 00:43:21.870
It's just some--
and then I realized.

00:43:21.870 --> 00:43:23.700
The way that I do
things isn't necessarily

00:43:23.700 --> 00:43:26.334
right in another culture or
another place in the world,

00:43:26.334 --> 00:43:27.250
in other conversation.

00:43:27.250 --> 00:43:28.249
It doesn't.

00:43:28.249 --> 00:43:30.540
Just because one way is right,
doesn't mean another way

00:43:30.540 --> 00:43:32.800
is wrong, too.

00:43:32.800 --> 00:43:36.300
And I think that's a very
interesting psychological,

00:43:36.300 --> 00:43:40.230
waiting or anchoring that
we've all been exposed to.

00:43:40.230 --> 00:43:44.130
If you go back to, I think
it was the 1950s and '60s,

00:43:44.130 --> 00:43:47.190
Edward Bernays was one of
the most incredible PR agents

00:43:47.190 --> 00:43:48.600
at the time.

00:43:48.600 --> 00:43:52.131
What he did, Marlborough,
smoking company, went to him

00:43:52.131 --> 00:43:53.880
and said, we don't
have any women smokers.

00:43:53.880 --> 00:43:55.230
What do we do about it?

00:43:55.230 --> 00:43:56.670
He went and did some research.

00:43:56.670 --> 00:43:59.630
He found out that women felt
a certain way about smoking

00:43:59.630 --> 00:44:01.320
and putting this
stick into the mouth

00:44:01.320 --> 00:44:04.120
was something that
they didn't want to do.

00:44:04.120 --> 00:44:08.710
So then he explored how the
relationship and the sort

00:44:08.710 --> 00:44:10.360
of branding behind it--

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:12.770
but explored what
does it mean for them.

00:44:12.770 --> 00:44:16.060
Explored the meaning and how
he could shift that meaning

00:44:16.060 --> 00:44:19.300
and made an
incredible difference.

00:44:19.300 --> 00:44:22.240
He hired 10 beautiful
women, the beginning

00:44:22.240 --> 00:44:25.402
of the march for female freedom,
gave them all cigarettes,

00:44:25.402 --> 00:44:27.610
lit them up, called the
press, took some photographs,

00:44:27.610 --> 00:44:28.380
and boom!

00:44:28.380 --> 00:44:31.570
Did that one event have a
huge impact on the sales

00:44:31.570 --> 00:44:34.360
that females were
smoking cigarettes for?

00:44:34.360 --> 00:44:36.070
It's really interesting for me.

00:44:36.070 --> 00:44:37.977
But the way that
we influence people

00:44:37.977 --> 00:44:40.060
and the psychological
messaging that we give them,

00:44:40.060 --> 00:44:42.460
whether it's commercials,
whether it's data

00:44:42.460 --> 00:44:45.220
that we analyze and show--

00:44:45.220 --> 00:44:47.740
I think a lot of
that intention has

00:44:47.740 --> 00:44:49.960
been set by someone
or something,

00:44:49.960 --> 00:44:52.962
mostly for reasons of
their own causes, right?

00:44:52.962 --> 00:44:54.670
I'm going to try and
sell you a Coca-Cola

00:44:54.670 --> 00:44:56.680
can no matter what
I can do, even

00:44:56.680 --> 00:45:01.252
if I'm stepping on a
Pepsi can in an advert.

00:45:01.252 --> 00:45:02.710
But I know, and
you know, that it's

00:45:02.710 --> 00:45:04.793
got like huge amounts of
sugar and a chemical that

00:45:04.793 --> 00:45:08.260
stops my mouth exploring
that there is too much sugar

00:45:08.260 --> 00:45:09.960
in my mouth.

00:45:09.960 --> 00:45:11.140
Is that fair or not fair?

00:45:11.140 --> 00:45:12.840
Well, it's FDA approved.

00:45:12.840 --> 00:45:14.300
OK, fine.

00:45:14.300 --> 00:45:17.550
So it's really interesting how
a lot of that research now, all

00:45:17.550 --> 00:45:19.980
of our experimentation
has allowed to us

00:45:19.980 --> 00:45:22.680
may be becoming more conscious
about certain things, and not.

00:45:22.680 --> 00:45:24.870
And I don't think
anything is written.

00:45:24.870 --> 00:45:27.540
I think we have an opportunity
to explore everything.

00:45:27.540 --> 00:45:29.989
Like a teacher that I used
to have in one of my classes

00:45:29.989 --> 00:45:30.780
when I was younger.

00:45:30.780 --> 00:45:33.120
She used to say, well, that's
just the way that it is.

00:45:33.120 --> 00:45:35.130
And I'm saying, well,
I don't think so.

00:45:35.130 --> 00:45:38.197
Well, something inside me
tells me it's not that way.

00:45:38.197 --> 00:45:40.780
But she would often say, well,
that's just the way that it is.

00:45:40.780 --> 00:45:42.600
So it's interesting.

00:45:42.600 --> 00:45:46.230
If you were to explore another
way of being, another language,

00:45:46.230 --> 00:45:48.420
another narrative,
another identity,

00:45:48.420 --> 00:45:52.360
and you had no holds
barred, who would you be?

00:45:56.500 --> 00:45:58.268
You can be anyone.

00:45:58.268 --> 00:45:58.768
Sorry.

00:45:58.768 --> 00:46:00.684
AUDIENCE: Maybe
the last question.

00:46:00.684 --> 00:46:03.080
